This is basically the same level of seriousness as those dialogues where like Hitler gets mad at Himmler in a wacky way for getting too excited over archeology or stories of "Soviet hero female sniper singlehandedly shoots 400 enemy soldiers"

I really like the pattern of someone being a famous politician, general, etc. and his son or grandson being a historian who has dedicated his career to studying him and documenting his life. Like the family line needed a generation extra to contemplate and ruminate over the man.

Like your dad was instrumental in winning some war, turning the country around, had great adventures. Maybe you can't live up to it fully, but you can set the record straight and write a few biography books to cement him in history. Then your own great grandson may pop off again.

In a way it reverses the stereotype dynamic because one imagines a historian as old, dignified, antiquated, etc. and the "man of action" as young, daring, etc. but here the "man of action" is already old and the historian is young and boyish compared to him. A complete opposite.
